<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ911226-0065</DOCNO><DOCID>911226-0065.</DOCID><HL>   Technology:   Applied Magnetics,   Lenders to Amend   Loan Agreements</HL><DATE>12/26/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B4</SO><CO>   APM</CO><MS>TECHNOLOGY (TEC)</MS><IN>COMPUTERS AND INFORMATION TECHNOLOGY (CPR)</IN><NS>EARNINGS PROJECTIONS (ERP)FINANCING AGREEMENTS (FNC)</NS><RE>CALIFORNIA (CA)NORTH AMERICA (NME)PACIFIC RIM (PRM)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   GOLETA, Calif. -- Applied Magnetics Corp., hurt by thedownturn in the computer industry, said it reached agreementwith its two principal banks to amend loan agreementscovering several credit facilities.   Applied Magnetics also said it expects revenue in itsfirst quarter ending Dec. 31 to be &quot;flat&quot; compared with about$100 million posted in the fourth quarter, a spokesman said.Second-quarter revenue will be &quot;lower than $100 million,&quot; hesaid.</LP><TEXT>   Under the loan agreements' revised terms, total creditavailable was reduced to $50 million from $67.5 million andis secured by substantially all of the company's domesticassets. About $40 million of loans are currently outstanding.Certain maturities were extended until April 1993 and theeffective interest rate was increased by one percentagepoint, the company said.   Applied Magnetics said it is now in compliance or hasobtained waivers of all covenants in the agreements. Themaker of magnetic recording heads for the computer industryhad been in technical default since posting a $26 millionloss in the fourth quarter ended Sept. 30.   &quot;This continues to be a difficult period for both AppliedMagnetics and the data storage industry,&quot; said Bill Anderson,president and chief executive officer. Management expectscost-reduction efforts to continue into the second quarterending March 31 as the backlog and order rate indicates lowerrevenue for that period, the company said.   Total employment has declined about 25% to 10,000 peoplefrom a peak of about 13,400 a year ago, a spokesman said.</TEXT></DOC>